<HEADLINE>
<P>
CORPORATE SNAPSHOT: IRVINE SENSORS, COSTA MESA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Nature of business: Develops and manufactures high-density computer 
electronics and infrared sensing devices 
</P>
<P>
 Total employees: 51. 
</P>
<P>
 In Orange County: 40 
</P>
<P>
 Stock listing in The Times: On Nasdaq: "Irvine" 
</P>
<P>
 Ticker symbol: "IRSN" 
</P>
<P>
 Friday's stock close: $9.25 
</P>
<P>
 One-week change: Up $0.25 
</P>
<P>
 Analyst review: "The prospects for Irvine Sensors depend to a large extent on 
its memory chip stacking technology. They have developed technology for 
thinning memory chips to something like the thickness of Glad wrap, stacking 
and bonding them. They can stack four memory chips in the space of one. It's a 
very sophisticated product and has very promising applications. It could 
replace the hard drives in personal and laptop computers with something the 
size of a credit card. The company's technology is first-rate, but in terms of 
its commercial viability, the company is heavily dependent on the agreement it 
signed with IBM in June, 1992, to produce the short stacks. Samples are just 
coming off the production lines now." 
</P>
<P>
 -- James L. Liuzzi, analyst, Cruttenden & Co., Irvine Revenue 
</P>
