<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHURCH HEARS KEVORKIAN PLEA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Jack Kevorkian began a petition drive Sunday to legalize assisted suicide in 
Michigan by urging about 700 churchgoers to join his crusade. 
</P>
<P>
 Kevorkian needs more than 250,000 signatures to place a constitutional 
amendment on the November ballot. In a speech between services at St. Paul's 
Presbyterian Church, Kevorkian spoke of the "right not to suffer." 
</P>
<P>
 Pastor Thomas Egglebeen invited him to speak. 
</P>
<P>
 The audience gave several standing ovations to Kevorkian, who has been present 
at the deaths of 20 people since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
 Two people holding Bibles over their heads briefly protested his appearance. 
</P>
