January 31, 1994, Monday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Special Section; Part JS; Page 2 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
73 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ANGELES TIMES SPECIAL REPORT; IMAGES OF THE NORTHRIDGE EARTHQUAKE; DAMAGE; 
A VIOLENT FORCE SHATTER WHAT HAD BEEN PAINSTAKINGLY BUILT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Everyone knew the magnitude 6.6 quake was, if not The Big One, at least A Big 
One.But few were prepared for the stark images that emerged with the cool light 
of day. 
</P>
<P>
 Shops and schools, buildings as familiar and hospitable as our own homes, lay 
in twisted ruin. Proof of the quake's injustice, the hand of destruction was 
not only heavy, but fickle. Entire blocks were torn up, while adjacent 
neighborhoods escaped untouched. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA013194-0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 008950 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
January 31, 1994, Monday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Special Section; Part JS; Page 4 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
97 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ANGELES TIMES SPECIAL REPORT; IMAGES OF THE NORTHRIDGE EARTHQUAKE; FLAMES; 
FIRE ESCAPES FROM THE CRACKS IN THE EARTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 If the serpent in the earth was the enemy, fire was next. 
</P>
<P>
 After the shaking stopped, the first words uttered in apartments and tract 
houses and mobile homes were frequently the almost hysterical command, "Turn 
off the gas!" Often, the order came too late. 
</P>
<P>
 Severed gas lines hissed from cracked foundations. Then, all it took was a 
spark for the flames to appear. Once started, they consumed everything in their 
path while firefighters, deprived of water by the quake, watch hopelessly. A 
hundred mobile homes burned to fragments of hot metal in three Sylmar parks 
alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA013194-0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 008951 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
