January 31, 1994, Monday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Special Section; Part JS; Page 7 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
83 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ANGELES TIMES SPECIAL REPORT; IMAGES OF THE NORTHRIDGE EARTHQUAKE; GRIEF; 
FOR SOME, A LOSS BEYOND CONSOLATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When we all were terrified when the quake hit, most of us, even those who had 
lost a home, breathed a little easier when the shaking stopped. 
</P>
<P>
 But for some, the fright yielded to horror when they discovered that loved 
ones had died. These people walked a separate path from the rest of us. While 
we dug out, they made funeral arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
 For them, the Northridge quake will never recede into the past as an anecdote 
to tell their grandchildren. It will always be part of their present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
