<LENGTH>
<P>
146 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ANGELES TIMES SPECIAL REPORT; IMAGES OF THE NORTHRIDGE EARTHQUAKE; 
RECOVERY; FRACTURED LIVES AWAIT THEIR BRICKS AND MORTAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Getting back to normal. 
</P>
<P>
 Just days ago, normal life in Southern California too often seemed 
uninteresting and uninviting. It was too violent, too crowded, too superficial. 
</P>
<P>
 But now, as damage figures spiral upward like numbers on those billboards that 
count the world's population, it's hard not to feel a certain nostalgia for the 
once noisy, now silent mall and commutes that took only an hour. 
</P>
<P>
 As the sound of jackhammers replaces sirens, we have learned that normal can 
be an elusive, precious thing. Photo Editors: Vanessa Barnes Hillian, 
Akili-Casundria Ramsess, George Wilhelm, Art Director: Kris Hofmann, Writer: 
John Johnson, News Editor: Larry Jones, Digital Images Editor: Mike Zacchino, 
Copy Editor: Edward Silver 
</P>
<P>
 For reprints of this section, please write: Quake Photo Retrospective, Times 
Valley Edition, 20000 Prairie St., Chatsworth, Calif. 91311 
</P>
